net.njcull.collections

Interface ArrayBackedCollection<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements maintained by this collection and backing list
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.util.Collection<E>, java.lang.Iterable<E>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    ArrayBackedSet<E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ImmutableArraySet, ImmutableHashedArraySet, ImmutableSortedArraySet

    public interface ArrayBackedCollection<E>
extends java.util.Collection<E>

    A Collection implemented by a backing array, and has a List view over the data.

    Version:
    10/01/2016.

      • toString

        static <E> java.lang.String toString(ArrayBackedCollection<E> c)
        Returns a string representation of this collection. The string representation consists of a sequence of the collection's elements in the order they are returned by its getAtIndex(int) method, enclosed in square brackets ("[]"). Adjacent elements are separated by the characters ", " (comma and space). Elements are converted to strings as by String.valueOf(Object).

        This implementation is handled as a static method rather than a default method because a default method cannot override any method of Object.

        Type Parameters:
        E - the type of elements in the collection
        Parameters:
        c - the collection from which the string will be generated
        Returns:
        a string representation of this collection

      • toArray

        static java.lang.Object[] toArray(ArrayBackedCollection<?> c)
        Returns an array containing all of the elements in the given collection. This method returns the elements in the same order as the getAtIndex(int) method.

        The returned array will be "safe" in that no references to it are maintained by this collection. In other words, this method allocates a new array even if this collection is backed by an array. The caller is thus free to modify the returned array.

        This method acts as bridge between array-based and collection-based APIs.

        This implementation is handled as a static method rather than a default method because a default method cannot override any method of Object.

        Parameters:
        c - the collection from which the elements are copied
        Returns:
        an array containing all the elements in this set

      • toArray

        static <T> T[] toArray(ArrayBackedCollection<?> c,
                       T[] a)
        Returns an array containing all of the elements in the given collection in proper sequence (from first to last element); the runtime type of the returned array is that of the specified array. If the collection fits in the specified array, it is returned therein. Otherwise, a new array is allocated with the runtime type of the specified array and the size of this collection.

        If the collection fits in the specified array with room to spare (i.e., the array has more elements than the collection), the element in the array immediately following the end of the collection is set to null. This is useful in determining the length of the collection only if the caller knows that the collection does not contain any null elements.

        This implementation is handled as a static method rather than a default method because a default method cannot override any method of Object.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the runtime type of the array to contain the collection
        Parameters:
        c - the collection from which the elements are copied
        a - the array into which the elements of the collection are to be stored, if it is big enough; otherwise, a new array of the same runtime type is allocated for this purpose.
        Returns:
        an array containing the elements of the collection
        Throws:
        java.lang.ArrayStoreException - if the runtime type of the specified array is not a supertype of the runtime type of every element in the given collection
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if the specified array is null
